              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">The Keys To A Good Tournament Experience</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=115"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=115"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=443">Douglas "Douglas" Harvilla</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 443 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">  Okay, you've got the decks and you're wearing your lucky t-shirt.  What now?  Now think about some little things you can do to make sure you have a good tournament.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">  These are some things you can do to make sure you, the other players, and the tournament director have a good time and want to come back next time.  And to make sure you're ready next time.<br>
<br>
- Try to show up early.  This lets you relax a bit and talk to friends and fellow players before the tournament.  If inspiration hits you, there is plenty of time to swap a couple cards into your decks.<br>
<br>
- Introduce yourself to your opponent if you don't know each other.  Friends can be made this way, and people are much more likely to return for the next tournament if they know some of the local players.<br>
<br>
- If it is a big, competitive event, try to get a good night's sleep first.  With few exceptions, tournaments either begin early in the day or run late into the evening.  Either way, you'll be at a distinct disadvantage without some rest.<br>
<br>
- When trying out a new deck for one side (Light/Dark), bring along a tried and true deck for the other side.  If you bring two brand new, unproven decks and neither of them work, you might not have much fun.<br>
<br>
- If you are a pretty consistent player, a loss in game 1 might be a bit discouraging.	Don't let it get you down.  Often a loss in game 1 will put you up against someone less experienced and give you an opportunity to build up differential and get back in contention.<br>
<br>
- After each game, go through it in your mind and see what worked and what didn't.  Discuss your games with other players in between rounds if there is time.	This makes each game a learning experience and also clears your mind to handle the next opponent.<br>
<br>
- Don't make excuses for a lost game.	This puts weight on your mind which will affect your performance, and can keep you from learning a valuable lesson.  We all do this from time to time, but it is a bad habit we should try to shake.<br>
<br>
- Before you leave, thank the tournament director.  This seems like a small detail, but when a dozen people remember to do it, it adds up.  And if you have to/decide to leave early, let someone know first.<br>
<br>
- Keep a box of potentially useful common and uncommon cards around.  Take it to tourneys with you.  You never know when you'll need these, or when a newer player will be interested in trading for uncommons.  Or when you can help a fellow player out.<br>
<br>
- Anything can happen.	We're dealing with cards here.  Remember this.  Whenever you begin to feel like you cannot win a game, or that you have to win a game, just tell yourself.  Anything can happen.<br>
<br>
- Perhaps the best advice I can give you is this.  Get a notebook or legal pad with plenty of pages.  When you play in a tournament, bring it along.  After each game, jot down your opponent's name and what kind of deck he/she was playing.  (this also helps you remember to introduce yourself)  Recap the events of the game, any notes to yourself about how the decks are working, and so on.<br>
  This can be very helpful and doesn't take much time.  It also helps you write tournament reports once you get back, and serve as a reminder to make necessary changes to your decks.  I've been doing this since my first tourney, and the folder of reports is a valuable resource to me.	</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=115"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=115"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=115" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
